            <div type="translation">
            <p>To Apollo Hylates and Apollo Caesar, Polyktetos, (son of) Timon, potter, (dedicated
                    this) on his own behalf, and also On[es---] (offered) the vow.</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>Originally preserved in five fragments from its shoulders and rim, the pithos has
                    been partially reconstructed with different materials during successive
                    archaeological campaigns. The letters are clear and well spaced. The potter
                    Polyktetos offered this ex-voto to Apollo Hylates, whose sanctuary at Kourion
                    was one of the main religious complexes on the island of Cyprus. The second
                    deity named, Apollo Caesar, likely refers to the emperor Trajan, as noted by
                    Mitford 1971. From the same sanctuary come numerous ceramic figurines, molded in
                    clay and dedicated as votive offerings to Apollo (cf. Byler 2022).</p></div>
            

